The paper deals with theoretical aspects of self-assembly models, specifically the Tile Assembly Model (TAM) and its variations. The paper discusses the computational power of different TAM models and their ability to simulate each other. This falls under the category of theoretical computer science (cs.THEORY). The paper also involves combinatorial and geometric aspects of self-assembly, which are relevant to discrete mathematics (cs.DM), computational geometry (cs.CG), and algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). Finally, the paper discusses the complexity of self-assembly models, which is relevant to computational complexity (cs.CC).
